# Riverpod Learning Guide

Follow this in order. Each concept builds on the previous one.

---

## Prerequisites
- Basic Flutter & Dart knowledge
- Understanding of StatefulWidget and setState
- Add `flutter_riverpod` to your pubspec.yaml
- Wrap your app with `ProviderScope` in main.dart

---

## Part 1 — Core Providers

**1. Provider**
The base and simplest provider. Holds a value that never changes on its own.
Use when you have a constant or computed value that doesn't need to update.

**2. StateProvider**
Holds a single simple value (int, String, bool) that can change.
Use for counters, toggles, tab index, or any single primitive value that changes.

**3. Consumer & ConsumerStatefulWidget**
Widgets that let you read and watch providers inside your UI.
Learn this before writing any UI — every widget that touches a provider needs this.

**4. StateNotifierProvider**
For complex state with multiple fields or multiple operations. Logic lives in a separate class.
Use when StateProvider is not enough — lists, forms, objects, multiple update methods.

**5. FutureProvider**
Handles a one-time async operation. Gives you loading, error, and data states automatically.
Use for API calls or any async task that runs once when a screen loads.

**6. StreamProvider**
Like FutureProvider but for continuous data that keeps updating over time.
Use for real-time data — Firebase snapshots, WebSockets, live feeds.

**7. API Calls with Riverpod**
Practical application of FutureProvider with a real REST API.
Covers how to structure models, providers, and UI together cleanly.
Do this before moving to modern providers.

**8. NotifierProvider**
Modern replacement for StateNotifierProvider. Cleaner syntax, same power.
Prefer this over StateNotifierProvider in all new projects.

**9. AsyncNotifierProvider**
Modern replacement for FutureProvider when you also need actions on top of async state.
Use when you need to fetch data AND also call methods like refresh, add, or delete.

---

## Part 2 — Modifiers

Learn these after you are comfortable with all providers above.
Modifiers are not new providers — they are add-ons that change how any provider behaves.

**10. Family Modifier**
Lets you pass an argument to a provider. Each unique argument creates its own instance.
Use when you need the same provider logic for different data — fetch by ID, filter by category.

**11. AutoDispose Modifier**
Automatically destroys a provider when no widget is watching it anymore.
Use for screen-specific providers to prevent memory leaks and avoid stale data.

**12. Family + AutoDispose Combined**
The most common real-world pattern. Use when you need both — parameterized and auto-cleaned providers.

---

## Part 3 — Advanced

**13. Provider Dependencies**
Providers that watch other providers. When a dependency changes, everything that depends on it updates automatically.
Use for derived state, filtered lists, or anything where one value depends on another.

---

## Quick Provider Picker

| Situation                   | Use
|                             |
| Constant or computed value  | Provider
| Simple value that changes   | StateProvider
| Complex state with methods  | NotifierProvider
| One-time async / API call   | FutureProvider
| Real-time / stream data     | StreamProvider
| Async state + actions       | AsyncNotifierProvider
| Provider needs an argument  | add .family
| Screen-specific provider    | add .autoDispose
| Provider depends on another | ref.watch() inside provider